Info data

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jboysen/mri-and-alzheimers

Context:

The Open Access Series of Imaging Studies (OASIS) is a project aimed at making MRI data sets of the brain freely available to the scientific community. By compiling and freely distributing MRI data sets, we hope to facilitate future discoveries in basic and clinical neuroscience. OASIS is made available by the Washington University Alzheimers Disease Research Center, Dr.Randy Buckner at the Howard Hughes Medical Institute (HHMI)( at Harvard University, the Neuroinformatics Research Group (NRG) at Washington University School of Medicine, and the Biomedical Informatics Research Network (BIRN).

Content:

Longitudinal MRI Data in Nondemented and Demented Older Adults: This set consists of a longitudinal collection of 150 subjects aged 60 to 96. Each subject was scanned on two or more visits, separated by at least one year for a total of 373 imaging sessions. For each subject, 3 or 4 individual T1-weighted MRI scans obtained in single scan sessions are included. The subjects are all right-handed and include both men and women. 72 of the subjects were characterized as nondemented throughout the study. 64 of the included subjects were characterized as demented at the time of their initial visits and remained so for subsequent scans, including 51 individuals with mild to moderate Alzheimers disease. Another 14 subjects were characterized as nondemented at the time of their initial visit and were subsequently characterized as demented at a later visit.

Acknowledgements:

When publishing findings that benefit from OASIS data, please include the following grant numbers in the acknowledgements section and in the associated Pubmed Central submission: P50 AG05681, P01 AG03991, R01 AG021910, P20 MH071616, U24 RR0213

dati1lev$coeff=(rep(c("Interc","Slope"),150))


temp=dati %>%
  group_by(Subject.ID) %>%
  summarize(Group=Group[1])


library(tidyr)

Commenti

Il modello testato: Age*Group+(1|Subject.ID) ammette solo intercetta casuale, mentre il coefficiente angolare (cio levoluzione nel tempo) uguale per tutti i soggetti (dello stesso Group vista linterazione imposta nella formula). E una assunzione ragionevole?

Potremmo quindi voler testare un modello pi flessibile, con coefficiente angolare specifico per ogni soggetto: Age*Group+(1+Age|Subject.ID)

mod=lmer(nWBV ~ Age*Group+(1+Age|Subject.ID),data=dati)
summary(mod)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [

Attenzione!!! optimizer (nloptwrap) convergence code: 0 (OK) boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular') Non siamo autorizzati ad usa questo modello, il controllo della probabilit di falsi positivi (errore di primo tipo) non garantito!!

Lapprocio di permutazione non parametrico, assume leffetto casuale anche per il coefficiente angolare dei soggetti e ci garantisce migliori propriet inferenziali.

Profiles Clustering

plot(dati1lev$Interc,dati1lev$Slope)

D=dist(dati1lev[,c("Interc","Slope")])
hc=hclust(D,method = "complete")
plot(hc)

clst=cutree(hc,2)
dati1lev$Cluster=clst
plot(dati1lev$Interc,dati1lev$Slope,col=dati1lev$Cluster)

dati1lev$Interc=scale(dati1lev$Interc)
dati1lev$Slope=scale(dati1lev$Slope)
D=dist(dati1lev[,c("Interc","Slope")])
hc=hclust(D,method = "complete")
plot(hc)

clst=cutree(hc,3)
dati1lev$Cluster=clst
plot(dati1lev$Interc,dati1lev$Slope,col=dati1lev$Cluster)

tab=table(dati1lev$Cluster,dati1lev$Group)
tab=tab[-3,]
chisq.test(tab)
